  "title": "Critical Zone",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c744c7c19cb9ae2f",
      "text": "The Earth's critical zone is the thin layer of the Earth's surface where rock, water, air, and living organisms interact to support life. It extends from the top of the vegetation canopy to the bottom of the groundwater zone, and includes the soil, water bodies, and the atmosphere."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3933c33b6d1e14c9",
      "text": "\nThe critical zone is the area where the processes that sustain life on Earth occur. It is where plants grow and take up nutrients, where water flows and is purified, and where the atmosphere interacts with the Earth's surface. The critical zone also plays an important role in regulating the global climate system, by storing and releasing carbon, water, and other greenhouse gases.\n\nThe critical zone is a complex system, and its properties and processes vary depending on the local geology, climate, and biology. However, there are some common features that are found across most critical zones, such as the presence of soils, rocks, water, and biota.\n\nUnderstanding the critical zone is important for many reasons, including the sustainable management of natural resources, predicting and mitigating the effects of environmental change, and protecting human health. As such, there is ongoing research and monitoring of the critical zone around the world, including through initiatives such as the Critical Zone Observatory network in the United States."
